{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PWPy52WQgZ1Dh4z4RT3WSa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the fault! Looking at the precondition's `apply` section (line 88-93):\n\n```yaml\n- command: |\n    kubectl -n mongodb exec mongodb-replica-0 -- mongosh --quiet --eval '\n    cfg = rs.conf();\n    cfg.members[1].host = \"mongodb-replica-1.{{params.fault_host_suffix}}.svc.cluster.local:27017\";\n    cfg.version += 1;\n    rs.reconfig(cfg);\n    '\n  sleep: 5\n```\nThe precondition injects a fault by reconfiguring member 1's hostname to point to `mongodb-replica-1.mongo-wrong.svc.cluster.local:27017` using the `fault_host_suffix` parameter, when it should actually be `mongodb-replica-1.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017`. Yet in the replica status output, both members 1 and 2 show as SECONDARY with health=1, which seems odd—though this might be because the precondition was reapplied as part of the chained workflow.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the fault injection might not have happened at all. The probe `mongo_env_ready` checks whether the statefulset exists using a kubectl command, and if that probe passes, the `on_probe_fail: skip` directive means the apply block (which contains the fault injection) gets skipped entirely. So the question is whether that probe actually passed and caused the fault injection to be bypassed.\n\nLooking at the precondition logs, the probe ran silently with no output, which suggests it succeeded. That would mean the apply was skipped and no fault was injected. Then the second precondition unit `mongo_seed_fixture` ran and inserted the missing documents since there weren't enough already.\n\nBut the error message says the replica set isn't healthy, so either there's a fault from an earlier stage, or I'm misunderstanding what's happening with the probe logic. So the replica set is actually healthy with all three members properly configured. The key insight is that the `mongo_env_ready` probe passed, which means the apply step containing the fault injection was skipped entirely—the misconfigured host entry was never actually injected into the system.\n\nNow I need to trace back through the workflow stages to understand what happened. Stage 04 was the MongoDB deployment step, so let me examine that more closely.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2894,"cache_read_input_tokens":36907,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2894},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ade8da74-2b06-49a8-b563-f004c927fc7e","uuid":"20e4a144-c2d4-4e32-aa9b-83c6dcfc187b","request_id":"req_011Ccfe9Z1UKDmxU6xnZzUz4"}
